---
layout: post
title: "Disc filesystem metadata"
categories: data
---

The CD-ROM file loading methods in _Tokimeki Memorial_ identify files by disc
sector ID rather than filename. In the original release, these filenames are
intact, but they're not used. The standard file read/write methods are called in
the main executable, but only for accessing memory cards, except for one
reference to the filename of the main executable itself.

The following article is the output of
[psximager](https://github.com/cebix/psximager), a program which can show the
start sector of files, as well as extract files. See Notes at the bottom of the
page for things of interest.

1. Table of Contents
{:toc}

### Notes

I found `psximager` tricky to compile, and at time of writing the main
repository does not produce ready-made builds. I used
[tatref's build](https://github.com/tatref/psximager/releases/tag/3.0) for
Linux, but there are various other builds around the Internet including for
Windows.

Next, `psximager` is tricky with multi-track rips. I had to fake it by renaming
both the .cue and the first track's .bin to the same name, and editing the .cue
to pretend the second track doesn't exist. This worked for the 1995 Limited
Edition release (which is what this output is from), but crashed on the 1997
Playstation the Best re-release.

Another easier to use tool which will also give you sector names for files is
[jPSXdec](https://www.github.com/m35/jpsxdec/), which can extract certain
graphics, audio, and video formats from a BIN. It's much easier to use.

The volume data here gives us some information about the project's development.
It has a creation date of 31 August 1995, which according to Wikipedia is 43
days before the game's release date of 13 October 1995.

The preparer ID is one K.Fukuhara, certainly
[Kenichi Fukuhara](https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,198521/), whose name
appears in game code in `exedir/name_ext.exn`, where it gives the surname,
forename, and nickname strings of 「福原」,「健一」, and
「ふくちゃん」respectively (Fukuhara, Kenichi, and Fuku-chan). Fukuhara's name
appears on a number of software patents, notably including 1995 Konami patent
[JP264563/95](https://patents.google.com/patent/EP0768105A3/en), where he is
named alongside Kouji Igarashi, Masaaki Suzuki and Masayuki Tarao on a patent
dated 12 October 1995, one day before the release of
_Tokimeki Memorial: Forever With You_. It patents a system of icons which
enlarge when the player moves the mouse over them.

The volume set ID gives the string SLPS00064VER110. I believe the code SLPS
means a third-party Japanese game. 00064 refers to the product code, which is
unique within the SLPS nmespace, and VER110 appears to refer to version 110 (or
perhaps v1.10) of this CD. SLPS00064 is the Limited Edition (Shokai Genteiban)
release, while SLPS00065 is the code game's standard release; it's interesting
that they actually pressed different CD-ROMs for what is probably an identical
game. However, it's worth noting that this still uses the code SLPS-00065
internally in reference to its memory card identifier, `bu00:BISLPS-00065`,
which ensures that save games made on one version can be loaded on another
without problem.

In comparison, the 1997 Playstation the Best re-release of the game has a volume
set ID of TOKIMEKIMEMORIALBEST (rather than the serial and version number) and
the volume idea is VX009J2 (rather than TOKIMEKIMEMORIAL). Again it's prepared
by (K_FUKUHARA), now with an underline. It's dated 25 December 1997. I wonder if
Fukuhara was actually working on Christmas day or just selected an arbitrary
date for some reason.

Both outputs are from the same version of the game.  For the first output, the
most valuable piece of information is the leftmost column, which provides file
sector addreses in hexadecimal and maps them to the actual filenames. When
examining the source code, this will make it possible in somecases to identify
which files are being loaded. The second output is similar but provides the
numbers in decimal.

The order in which the XAudio files appear on the disc is interesting, since
they're out of alphabetical order and also don't match the internal ID numbers.
Fujisaki Shiori's file appears first, followed by the player's male friend
Yoshio and then his sister Yumi. All but one of the other voiced characters
appear thereafter in alphabetical order until we reach `etc.xa` and `bgm378.xa`,
and finally Megumi Mikihara (Shiori's friend). Why did Megumi get stuck at the
end? It's a mystery.
